THOUGHT: The crash happens at Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy) in VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute. On AIX p32, StartIdx0 can be a pointer or an integer of a different size, making a truncation invalid for constants, triggering ConstantExpr::getCast assertion. The safe fix is to replace unconditional trunc with a guarded integer cast: if the source is integer, use CreateIntCast to IntStepTy (which will choose trunc or extend as needed); if it’s a pointer, first cast to an integer of the same bit width as the pointer, then cast to IntStepTy. This avoids creating an invalid ConstantExpr trunc. I will edit VPlanRecipes.cpp to implement this guarded cast at line ~2130.

```bash
applypatch << 'EOF'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp
@@
-    StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);
+    // Ensure we only perform legal integer casts. If StartIdx0 is a pointer,
+    // cast it to an integer of the pointer's bit width first, then cast to
+    // the desired IntStepTy. If it's an integer, use CreateIntCast which
+    // handles truncation/extension as needed.
+    if (StartIdx0->getType()->isIntegerTy()) {
+      StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateIntCast(StartIdx0, IntStepTy, /*isSigned=*/false);
+    } else if (StartIdx0->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
+      Type *PtrIntTy = Builder.getIntPtrTy(StartIdx0->getType());
+      Value *PtrAsInt = Builder.CreatePtrToInt(StartIdx0, PtrIntTy);
+      StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateIntCast(PtrAsInt, IntStepTy, /*isSigned=*/false);
+    } else {
+      // As a fallback, avoid creating an invalid constant expression cast.
+      StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateBitCast(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);
+    }
*** End Patch
EOF
```

