THOUGHT: The assertion originates from an unconditional CreateTrunc on StartIdx0, which can be non-integer (e.g., pointer-derived) for certain targets like AIX p32, causing an invalid ConstantExpr cast. To fix, I will replace the truncation with a guarded cast: if StartIdx0 is integer, use CreateIntCast to IntStepTy; if it's a pointer, convert to an integer of pointer width via CreatePtrToInt, then IntCast to IntStepTy; otherwise, fallback to BitCast to avoid illegal constant truncations.

```bash
sed -i '2130c\    // Ensure we only perform legal integer casts. If StartIdx0 is a pointer,
    // cast it to an integer of the pointer'''s bit width first, then cast to
    // the desired IntStepTy. If it'''s an integer, use CreateIntCast which
    // handles truncation/extension as needed.
    if (StartIdx0->getType()->isIntegerTy()) {
      StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateIntCast(StartIdx0, IntStepTy, /*isSigned=*/false);
    } else if (StartIdx0->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
      Type *PtrIntTy = Builder.getIntPtrTy(StartIdx0->getType());
      Value *PtrAsInt = Builder.CreatePtrToInt(StartIdx0, PtrIntTy);
      StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateIntCast(PtrAsInt, IntStepTy, /*isSigned=*/false);
    } else {
      // As a fallback, avoid creating an invalid constant expression cast.
      StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateBitCast(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);
    }' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp && submit-patch
```

